## 5. Permissions Strategy

```python
# accounts/permissions.py

class IsStudent(BasePermission):
    def has_permission(self, request, view):
        return request.user.is_authenticated and request.user.role == 'student'

class IsDoctor(BasePermission):
    def has_permission(self, request, view):
        return request.user.is_authenticated and request.user.role == 'doctor'

class IsAdmin(BasePermission):
    def has_permission(self, request, view):
        return request.user.is_authenticated and request.user.role == 'admin'
```

ViewSets will combine these with DRF's `permission_classes` per action:

```python
def get_permissions(self):
    if self.action == 'create':
        return [IsDoctor()]
    if self.action in ['list', 'retrieve']:
        return [IsAuthenticated()]  # further filtered in get_queryset
    return [IsAdmin()]
```

---

## 6. Authentication Flow

```mermaid
sequenceDiagram
    participant C as Client
    participant S as Server
    C->>S: POST /api/v1/auth/login/ {email, password}
    S-->>C: {access_token, refresh_token, user role}
    C->>S: GET /api/v1/records/ (Authorization: Bearer <access>)
    S-->>C: Filtered records based on role
    Note over C,S: When access token expires
    C->>S: POST /api/v1/auth/token/refresh/ {refresh_token}
    S-->>C: {new access_token}
```

---

## 7. Key Design Decisions

> [!IMPORTANT]
> **Custom User model with email login** — must be set up before the first migration. Changing the user model after migrations exist is extremely difficult.

1. **Single User model with `role` field** instead of separate Student/Doctor/Admin models — simpler auth, single JWT pipeline.
2. **ViewSet-per-model** pattern — consistent CRUD across all modules.
3. **Queryset filtering by role** — students only see their own records; doctors see records they created; admin sees everything.
4. **AI Assistant deferred** — marked as optional / phase 2. Can be added as a simple view that calls an external API using the student's medical records as context.

---

